<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
    <article class="min-h-screen bg-slate-50 py-12 px-4 sm:px-6">
        <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto space-y-8">
            <header class="space-y-4 text-center">
                <div
                    class="inline-block bg-amber-100 text-amber-700 px-4 py-1 rounded-full text-sm font-bold mb-4"
                >
                    For Employers
                </div>
                <h1
                    class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-slate-900 tracking-tight leading-tight"
                >
                    BC PNP <span class="text-amber-600">Employer Guide</span>
                </h1>
                <p
                    class="text-lg text-slate-600 max-w-2xl mx-auto leading-relaxed"
                >
                    Want to help your foreign worker get permanent residence?
                    Here's everything you need to know about supporting a BC PNP
                    application.
                </p>
            </header>

            <div
                class="prose prose-lg prose-slate max-w-none bg-white p-8 sm:p-12 rounded-[2rem] border border-slate-100 shadow-sm"
            >
                <h2>Why Support BC PNP Applications?</h2>
                <p>
                    Helping employees get permanent residence benefits your
                    business:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Retain talent:</strong> Employees with PR are more
                        likely to stay long-term
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>No more permit renewals:</strong> PRs don't need work
                        permit extensions
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Improved morale:</strong> Employees appreciate employer
                        support
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Access to larger talent pool:</strong> Attract workers
                        willing to relocate
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Employer Eligibility Requirements</h2>
                <p>
                    To support a BC PNP application, your business must meet
                    these criteria:
                </p>

                <h3>Business Structure</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Established and operating in British Columbia</li>
                    <li>Registered with BC Registries and in good standing</li>
                    <li>Has a valid municipal business license</li>
                    <li>Operates from a permanent physical location in BC</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Employee Count Requirements</h3>
                <div class="not-prose overflow-x-auto my-6">
                    <table class="min-w-full text-left text-sm">
                        <thead class="bg-gray-100 border-b border-gray-200">
                            <tr>
                                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-slate-900"
                                    >Business Age</th
                                >
                                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-slate-900"
                                    >Metro Vancouver</th
                                >
                                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-slate-900"
                                    >Outside Metro Van</th
                                >
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-100">
                            <tr>
                                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium"
                                    >Operating 1+ year</td
                                >
                                <td class="px-4 py-3"
                                    >3+ full-time employees (or equivalent)</td
                                >
                                <td class="px-4 py-3">1+ full-time employee</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium"
                                    >Operating less than 1 year</td
                                >
                                <td class="px-4 py-3">5+ full-time employees</td
                                >
                                <td class="px-4 py-3">3+ full-time employees</td
                                >
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <h3>Employment Terms Requirements</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Full-time:</strong> Job must be 30+ hours per week
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Indeterminate:</strong> No end date (permanent position)
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Competitive wage:</strong> Must meet or exceed median
                        wage for the occupation
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Located in BC:</strong> Work must be performed in
                        British Columbia
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <div
                    class="bg-red-50 p-6 rounded-xl text-sm border border-red-200 mb-8"
                >
                    <strong>‚ö†Ô∏è Not Eligible:</strong> Employers on the BC PNP ineligible
                    employer list, businesses with regulatory violations, or employers
                    with a history of non-compliance cannot support applications.
                </div>

                <h2>Documents You Need to Provide</h2>

                <h3>1. BC PNP Employer Declaration</h3>
                <p>
                    Official form signed by an authorized representative (owner,
                    director, or HR executive) confirming:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Business details and contact information</li>
                    <li>Job offer specifics</li>
                    <li>Declaration that information is accurate</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>2. Job Offer Letter</h3>
                <p>On company letterhead, including:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Employee's full legal name</li>
                    <li>Job title and NOC code (2021 version)</li>
                    <li>Detailed job duties</li>
                    <li>Wage or salary</li>
                    <li>Hours per week (must be 30+)</li>
                    <li>
                        Start date and employment type (full-time, permanent)
                    </li>
                    <li>Work location</li>
                    <li>Supervisor's contact information and signature</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>3. Business Registration Documents</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Certificate of Incorporation</strong> from BC Registries
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>BC Company Summary</strong> (recent, showing active
                        status)
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Municipal business license</strong> (valid and current)
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <h3>4. Additional Documents (If Requested)</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Organizational chart showing employee's position</li>
                    <li>
                        Proof of recruitment efforts for domestic candidates
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Financial statements demonstrating ability to pay wages
                    </li>
                    <li>T4 Summary or WCB statements proving employee count</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Employer Costs</h2>
                <div class="not-prose overflow-x-auto my-6">
                    <table class="min-w-full text-left text-sm">
                        <thead class="bg-gray-100 border-b border-gray-200">
                            <tr>
                                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-slate-900"
                                    >Fee Type</th
                                >
                                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-slate-900"
                                    >Amount</th
                                >
                                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-slate-900"
                                    >Who Pays</th
                                >
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-100">
                            <tr>
                                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium"
                                    >BC PNP Application Fee</td
                                >
                                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-bold">$1,475</td>
                                <td class="px-4 py-3"
                                    >Employee (employer can assist)</td
                                >
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium"
                                    >LMIA Fee (if applicable)</td
                                >
                                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-bold">$1,000</td>
                                <td class="px-4 py-3">Employer only</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium"
                                    >Staff time for documentation</td
                                >
                                <td class="px-4 py-3">Varies</td>
                                <td class="px-4 py-3">Employer</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <div
                    class="bg-amber-50 p-6 rounded-xl text-sm border border-amber-200 mb-8"
                >
                    <strong>üí° Note:</strong> While employees typically pay the BC
                    PNP fee, many employers choose to reimburse or share these costs
                    as a retention benefit.
                </div>

                <h2>Step-by-Step Process</h2>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Confirm eligibility:</strong>
                        <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 mt-1">
                            Ensure your business meets all employer
                            requirements.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Provide employment documentation:</strong>
                        <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 mt-1">
                            Give your employee a proper job offer letter and
                            reference letters.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Employee registers in SIRS:</strong>
                        <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 mt-1">
                            Your employee creates their BC PNP profile using
                            information from your job offer.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Wait for invitation:</strong>
                        <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 mt-1">
                            Employee waits in the pool; you continue normal
                            employment.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Complete Employer Declaration:</strong>
                        <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 mt-1">
                            When invited, sign the official BC PNP employer
                            form.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Respond to verification:</strong>
                        <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 mt-1">
                            BC PNP may contact you to verify the job
                            offer‚Äîrespond promptly.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Continue employment:</strong>
                        <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 mt-1">
                            Maintain employment until employee receives PR.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>

                <h2>Employer Responsibilities</h2>

                <h3>During Processing</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Keep the employee employed in the same position</li>
                    <li>
                        Respond to BC PNP verification requests within stated
                        deadlines
                    </li>
                    <li>Notify BC PNP of any changes to employment terms</li>
                    <li>Maintain accurate payroll records</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>After Nomination</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        Continue employment until employee receives PR (6-18
                        months)
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Provide Work Permit Support Letter requests if needed
                    </li>
                    <li>Allow time for medical exams and appointments</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Common Employer Mistakes</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Vague job duties:</strong> Ensure duties match the
                        NOC description precisely
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Below-median wages:</strong> Offering wages too low
                        for the occupation raises red flags
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Incomplete letterhead:</strong> Include full company
                        address and contact information
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Delayed responses:</strong> Not responding to BC PNP
                        verification requests in time
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Terminated employee:</strong> Firing the employee
                        during processing cancels their application
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

                <h3>Can I support multiple employees?</h3>
                <p>
                    Yes. There's no limit to how many BC PNP applications you
                    can support, as long as each position is genuine and meets
                    requirements.
                </p>

                <h3>What if the employee changes positions?</h3>
                <p>
                    If the employee changes roles significantly, BC PNP must be
                    notified. Major changes may require a new application.
                </p>

                <h3>Can I charge the employee for my time?</h3>
                <p>
                    No. IRCC and BC PNP prohibit employers from charging workers
                    for immigration-related costs including LMIA fees and
                    administrative time.
                </p>

                <h3>What if I need to lay off the employee?</h3>
                <p>
                    Notify BC PNP immediately. The employee may be able to find
                    a new employer and transfer their application, but this
                    isn't guaranteed.
                </p>

                <h2>Regional Employer Benefits</h2>
                <p>
                    Employers located outside Metro Vancouver enjoy significant advantages under the BC PNP program. The provincial government actively encourages immigration to smaller communities and regional areas, offering tangible benefits to businesses that hire and support foreign workers in these locations.
                </p>

                <h3>Lower Employee Count Requirements</h3>
                <p>
                    One of the most practical benefits for regional employers is the reduced staffing threshold needed to qualify as an eligible employer:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Established businesses (1+ year):</strong> Need only 1 full-time employee compared to 3 in Metro Vancouver
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Newer businesses (under 1 year):</strong> Need 3 full-time employees compared to 5 in Metro Vancouver
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Easier qualification:</strong> Smaller businesses can participate in the program sooner
                    </li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    This lower threshold acknowledges the reality that many regional businesses operate with smaller teams while still providing essential services to their communities.
                </p>

                <h3>Regional Scoring Bonuses</h3>
                <p>
                    The BC PNP Skills Immigration Registration System (SIRS) awards bonus points to candidates with job offers outside Metro Vancouver:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Regional district bonus:</strong> Up to 10 additional points for jobs in regional areas
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Lower score requirements:</strong> Regional draws often have cutoff scores 20-40 points lower than general draws
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Targeted regional draws:</strong> BC PNP occasionally runs draws specifically for regional candidates
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <div
                    class="bg-green-50 p-6 rounded-xl text-sm border border-green-200 mb-8"
                >
                    <strong>Regional Advantage:</strong> Communities like Kelowna, Prince George, Kamloops, Nanaimo, and Vernon are considered regional for BC PNP purposes. Employers in these growing cities can attract talent more easily due to lower competitive thresholds.
                </div>

                <h3>Regional Communities Outside Metro Vancouver</h3>
                <p>
                    For BC PNP purposes, "outside Metro Vancouver" includes all of BC except the following municipalities: Vancouver, Burnaby, Richmond, Surrey, Delta, Langley (City and Township), Coquitlam, Port Coquitlam, Port Moody, New Westminster, North Vancouver (City and District), West Vancouver, White Rock, Maple Ridge, Pitt Meadows, Bowen Island, Anmore, Belcarra, and Lions Bay.
                </p>

                <h2>Industry-Specific Considerations</h2>
                <p>
                    Different industries face unique challenges and opportunities when supporting BC PNP applications. Understanding sector-specific pathways can help employers choose the most effective approach for their workers.
                </p>

                <h3>Healthcare Sector</h3>
                <p>
                    Healthcare employers benefit from dedicated BC PNP pathways designed to address critical shortages:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Health Authority stream:</strong> Specifically for workers employed by BC health authorities in priority occupations
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Priority processing:</strong> Healthcare occupations like nurses, medical technologists, and care aides receive expedited consideration
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Lower language requirements:</strong> Some healthcare roles may have reduced language requirements through the Health Authority stream
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Direct nominations:</strong> Health authorities can nominate workers directly without going through the general SIRS pool
                    </li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    Private healthcare facilities, clinics, and long-term care homes can support applications through the regular Skilled Worker stream while highlighting the critical nature of healthcare roles.
                </p>

                <h3>Technology Sector</h3>
                <p>
                    BC's Tech Pilot has been a game-changer for technology employers:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>29 priority occupations:</strong> Includes software developers, data scientists, UX designers, systems analysts, and IT managers
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Weekly draws:</strong> Tech stream candidates are invited through weekly targeted draws, ensuring faster processing
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>No minimum score:</strong> Tech stream invitations are based on registration date rather than score competition
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Startup-friendly:</strong> Even newer tech companies can support applications if they meet basic employer requirements
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <div
                    class="bg-blue-50 p-6 rounded-xl text-sm border border-blue-200 mb-8"
                >
                    <strong>Tech Tip:</strong> Ensure your job title and duties clearly align with one of the 29 eligible Tech Pilot NOC codes. Ambiguous titles like "Growth Hacker" or "Ninja Developer" should be mapped to standard NOC occupations.
                </div>

                <h3>Construction and Trades</h3>
                <p>
                    Construction employers can support skilled tradespeople through BC PNP:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Skilled Worker stream:</strong> Most construction roles qualify under TEER 0, 1, 2, or 3 categories
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Entry Level and Semi-Skilled (ELSS):</strong> Some construction helper and labourer positions may qualify through ELSS
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Certification requirements:</strong> Ensure workers hold or are working toward required BC trades certifications
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Regional projects:</strong> Construction projects outside Metro Vancouver benefit from regional bonuses
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Hospitality and Tourism</h3>
                <p>
                    Hospitality employers face unique considerations due to the nature of the industry:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>ELSS pathway:</strong> Many hotel, restaurant, and tourism roles qualify under the Entry Level and Semi-Skilled stream
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>NOC requirements:</strong> Management positions (hotel managers, food service managers) may qualify for Skilled Worker stream
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Regional tourism:</strong> Resort communities like Whistler, Tofino, and ski destinations benefit from regional advantages
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Year-round employment:</strong> Seasonal positions do not qualify; employers must offer permanent, year-round work
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Compliance and Audits</h2>
                <p>
                    BC PNP takes employer compliance seriously. Understanding the verification process helps employers prepare and avoid complications that could delay or jeopardize their employee's application.
                </p>

                <h3>What Happens During Employer Verification</h3>
                <p>
                    After an application is submitted, BC PNP may conduct employer verification through several methods:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Document review:</strong> Officers examine business registration, financial documents, and employment records
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Phone verification:</strong> BC PNP may call your business to confirm the job offer and speak with management
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Site visits:</strong> In some cases, officers may visit your workplace to verify operations
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Cross-referencing:</strong> Information is checked against CRA records, WorkSafeBC data, and other government databases
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <h3>How to Prepare for Verification</h3>
                <p>
                    Proactive preparation ensures smooth verification:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Designate a contact person:</strong> Ensure someone knowledgeable can respond to BC PNP inquiries
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Keep records organized:</strong> Maintain payroll records, T4s, and employee files in accessible order
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Brief your team:</strong> Inform reception and management that BC PNP may call to verify employment
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Document the position:</strong> Keep an organizational chart showing where the employee fits
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Maintain consistency:</strong> Ensure job duties, wages, and hours match what was declared in the application
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Common Audit Triggers</h3>
                <p>
                    Certain situations may trigger enhanced scrutiny from BC PNP:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Multiple applications:</strong> Employers supporting many applications in a short period
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Inconsistent information:</strong> Discrepancies between application details and business records
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Unusual wage structures:</strong> Wages significantly above or below market rates for the position
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Previous complaints:</strong> History of worker complaints or compliance issues
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>New businesses:</strong> Companies with limited operating history may face additional verification
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Industry patterns:</strong> Sectors with known compliance issues may receive extra scrutiny
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <div
                    class="bg-red-50 p-6 rounded-xl text-sm border border-red-200 mb-8"
                >
                    <strong>Warning:</strong> Employers found to have provided false information, created fake positions, or engaged in document fraud will be added to the BC PNP ineligible employer list and may face legal consequences. This also invalidates all pending and approved applications associated with that employer.
                </div>

                <h2>Supporting Multiple Streams</h2>
                <p>
                    As an employer, you may have employees who qualify for different BC PNP streams. Understanding each pathway helps you provide appropriate support and documentation.
                </p>

                <h3>Skilled Worker Stream</h3>
                <p>
                    The most common pathway for professional and skilled workers:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Eligible occupations:</strong> TEER 0, 1, 2, or 3 (professional, technical, and skilled trades)
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Employer requirements:</strong> Standard business eligibility requirements apply
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Employee requirements:</strong> Usually needs 2+ years of relevant experience, CLB 4+ language scores
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Your role:</strong> Provide job offer letter, employer declaration, and business documents
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Entry Level and Semi-Skilled (ELSS) Stream</h3>
                <p>
                    For workers in occupations requiring less formal training:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Eligible occupations:</strong> TEER 4 and 5 occupations in tourism, hospitality, food processing, and long-haul trucking
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Regional requirement:</strong> Position must be located outside Metro Vancouver
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Duration requirement:</strong> Employee must have worked for you for 9+ consecutive months
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Your role:</strong> Same documentation plus proof of 9+ months continuous employment
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Health Authority Stream</h3>
                <p>
                    Exclusively for BC health authority employees:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Eligible employers:</strong> Only BC's six health authorities (Fraser Health, Vancouver Coastal, Interior Health, Island Health, Northern Health, Provincial Health Services)
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Priority occupations:</strong> Nurses, allied health professionals, medical technologists, and support workers
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Direct nomination:</strong> Health authorities work directly with BC PNP on nominations
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Employer coordination:</strong> HR departments handle most paperwork internally
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <h3>BC PNP Tech Stream</h3>
                <p>
                    Accelerated pathway for technology workers:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>29 NOC codes:</strong> Specific technology occupations including developers, engineers, and analysts
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Weekly invitations:</strong> Tech candidates receive invitations every week
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Any BC location:</strong> Unlike ELSS, Tech stream works for Metro Vancouver positions
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Your role:</strong> Ensure job title and duties clearly match an eligible Tech NOC code
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <div
                    class="bg-amber-50 p-6 rounded-xl text-sm border border-amber-200 mb-8"
                >
                    <strong>Multi-Stream Tip:</strong> If an employee could qualify under multiple streams, discuss with them (or their immigration consultant) which pathway offers the best chance of success based on their qualifications and your business location.
                </div>

                <h2>2026 Updates for Employers</h2>
                <p>
                    The BC PNP landscape has changed significantly in 2025-2026. Employers should understand current program dynamics to set realistic expectations and support their employees effectively.
                </p>

                <h3>Reduced Nomination Allocations</h3>
                <p>
                    BC's provincial nomination allocation has been reduced as part of federal efforts to manage immigration levels:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Fewer nominations available:</strong> BC received a reduced allocation compared to previous years
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Higher competition:</strong> More applicants competing for fewer spots means higher score requirements
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Longer wait times:</strong> Employees may wait longer in the SIRS pool before receiving invitations
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Strategic applications:</strong> Timing and stream selection are more important than ever
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Priority Sectors for 2026</h3>
                <p>
                    BC PNP continues to prioritize certain sectors based on labour market needs:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Healthcare:</strong> Remains the top priority with dedicated draws and accelerated processing
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Technology:</strong> BC Tech Pilot continues with weekly draws for 29 NOC codes
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Skilled trades:</strong> Construction and maintenance trades remain in demand
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Childcare:</strong> Early childhood educators receive targeted support
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Regional positions:</strong> Jobs outside Metro Vancouver continue to receive scoring bonuses
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <h3>What Employers Should Know</h3>
                <p>
                    Key considerations for employers supporting BC PNP applications in 2026:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Set realistic timelines:</strong> The process from registration to PR may take 18-24+ months in the current environment
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Maximize employee scores:</strong> Higher wages, regional locations, and relevant experience all add points
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Consider stream selection:</strong> Tech and Health Authority streams may offer faster processing than general Skilled Worker
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Maintain employment:</strong> Continued employment throughout the process is essential
